quent questions about standardizing the process, instead offering general ideas without connecting them back to the specific challenges and details outlined in the reading, such as Dan Evans\'s unique expertise and time commitment.","question":"Q3. Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','liberal',1,3,'the hard questions that were asked','more help when i asked questions','gemini-2.5-flash','gemini-2.5-pro','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: what are the core restaurant operations currently?\n\nCEO: Good question, STUDENT. Our core restaurant operation, as you\'ve read, is a "fast casual" pizza restaurant. We focus on quick service, a healthy menu, and our social cause of donating a meal to Malawi for every meal purchased. We\'ve built a strong brand around this model.\n\nNow, let\'s bring it back to the main question. **How does our catering business fit into or diverge from these core operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: what do you think?\n\nCEO: STUDENT, I\'m here to hear *your* analysis. You\'ve read the case. I\'m looking for your informed perspective on whether catering aligns with our core restaurant operations or pulls us away from them.\n\n**What specific facts from the case lead you to believe catering is either a good fit or a distraction?**\n\nSTUDENT: I think that we should continue to cater because of the high profit margins\n\nCEO: That\'s a solid point, STUDENT. The case does mention that catering is the "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." I appreciate you grounding your recommendation in a specific fact.\n\nHowever, profitability isn\'t the only factor we need to consider. The case also highlights that our catering operation, as it currently stands, is "an ex