could be shifted towards self-service or made more efficient without Dan\'s direct involvement? And what specific facts from the case support your assertion that these parts can be standardized?\n\nSTUDENT: Dan is what we would consider a bottleneck in the process. A standard operating procedure with clear expectations and criteria should be made. This will allow a trained employee to quote based on set criteria freeing Kent to work on the scaling process.\n\nCEO: You\'re right, STUDENT, Dan is a bottleneck. But simply saying "a standard operating procedure with clear expectations and criteria should be made" is too high-level. I need specifics.\n\nBased on the case facts, what *specific tasks* does Dan currently perform that could be standardized and delegated to another trained employee, reducing his direct involvement with clients? And what would be the immediate benefit of doing so, according to the case?\n\nSTUDENT: A discussion on different catering sections such as wedding, event and so on. Based on number of pizzas and economies of scales, and time a price can be reached. This would make it easy to easily and quickly quote\n\nCEO: That\'s a good start, STUDENT. You\'re focusing on the pricing aspect. The case states that "Evans priced every event himself; the price was based on the COGS for each type of pizza, the size of the event, the labor required, and the normal catering margin."\n\nIf we were to standardize this, how exactly would we remove Evans\'s personal "intuition, experience, and knowledge" from the pricing process, and what specific information from the case would be necessary to create a standardized pricing tool or matrix that another employee could use?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nST