INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('86cf1b51-fff5-4f98-a029-e3dcda475198','2025-10-27 16:03:35','f8a54b80-86c4-42c2-bbc1-56c6d0cb2fd3',14,'Macie demonstrated a solid grasp of the case material, effectively using details to support her arguments. She provided clear recommendations, such as continuing catering due to its profitability and marketing benefits, and suggested hiring an event planner to alleviate Dan Evans\' workload. While her arguments were well-justified, the conversation concluded before she could fully elaborate on the feasibility of hiring a dedicated catering staff member within Malawi\'s current operational model.','[{"score":5,"feedback":"Macie consistently referenced specific points and quotes from the reading material, demonstrating a strong understanding of the case facts and company context.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Macie provided generally strong answers, identifying key opportunities and risks. Her suggestion to hire an event planner was a clear attempt to address the bottlenecks identified. The conversation ended before she could fully develop her final point regarding the justification for a new dedicated role.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Macie consistently justified her answers by directly quoting or extensively paraphrasing relevant information from the case, demonstrating strong analytical skills in connecting her recommendations to the provided material.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','strict',0,4,'I liked how kent kind of fought back with me and challenged my ideas.. I thought it was good to have to defend my point of view and give specific evidence','I think that if there were some more creative questions it could be helpful!','gemini-2.5-flash-lite','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: I would recomend staying in the catering business but also altering some of your catering processes\n\nCEO: That\'s a bold recommendation, STUDENT. Tell me, what specifically in the case leads you to believe we should continue with catering, despite the challenges?\n\nSTUDENT: The case says "Catering fit nicely into the day-to-day operations of the restaurant. For the most part, catering didnt require a lot of extra effort outside of the restaurants normal operations. " The scheduling was the most time consuming and difficult part but it was still considered profitable especially because Malawi\'s is only catehring to around 10 events per year\n\nCEO: You\'re right that the case mentions catering fitting into daily operations and its profitability. However, you\'ve highlighted the scheduling as a difficult part, and you\'ve also noted that Malawi\'s is only catering about ten events per year.\n\nConsidering this, how do you reconcile the idea of "staying in the catering business" with the fact that the current scale is very small and that the planning process, as described, takes a significant amount of Dan Evans\' time  anywhere from 3 to 10 hours per event?\n\nSTUDENT: I would say that the cost of scheduling is worth it because cetering is also a useful advertising tool that malawais can use. If they cater for a big event and it goes well they are protecting brand image and they are building trust and hopefully a connection with the customers who use their catering services! also the case tells us that "Catering was seen as a much more profitable model than traditional restaurant service because of the low overhead, and higher profit margin"\n\nCEO: Those are good points, STUDENT. The case does indeed state that catering is more profitable due to lower overhead and higher margins. It also mentions that catering serves as a word-of-mouth marketing tool.\n\nHowever, you\'ve focused on the benefits. What are the *risks* associated with this advertising and brand-building approach, especially given the operational challenges you mentioned earlier with Dan Evans\' time commitment and the limited number of events?\n\nSTUDENT: The risks are if the catering does not go well it could seriously hurt our brand reputation. In addition time is a resource and it takes time to plan an event well and taking time out of Dan Evans schedule to plan is time that he is not spending managing the restruant itself. I\'d reccomend that Malawis hire a event planner to better allow Dan to focus on the restruant itself and to better expand the catering business because it is profitable, and would help brand image with marketing. I think if you had a focused team dedicated to vcetering you could also minimize the risks that come from the limited number of events and you could target customers and advertise your catering services more.\n\nCEO: That\'s an interesting recommendation, STUDENT, proposing to hire an event planner. But where in the case does it support the idea that we should hire a new person specifically for event planning to address these issues?\n\nSTUDENT: It does not give evidence to support this specifically in the case, however the case also says " they were always directed to Evans, who would ask a few specific questions\nto determine the date (preventing scheduling conflicts), the type of event, and the expected number\nof attendees. At this time, he would also ask a few initial questions to get a broad picture of the\nclients needs and would then set up an appointment to discuss the clients expectations in more\ndetail. While Evans would occasionally hold this meeting over the phone, he disliked that approach,\npreferring to have as much direct interaction with the client as possible. Evans knew that catering\nevents commanded premium pricing, and he wanted the customers to feel as though they were\nreceiving the highest degree of attention and customization.\nThere were two types of clients for Malawis catering: professional event planners and non-\nprofessionalseveryday people with little to no experience planning events. This distinction made\nall the difference in the planning process because of the knowledge and skills the client contributed\nto the process. Professional event planners understood the food service industry, had experience\nwith food quantities and attendee expectations, knew where to place the catering team, and\nunderstood in general what questions needed to be asked. Evans enjoyed working with\nprofessional planners because they were fast and efficient. His meetings with them usually lasted\nthirty minutes unless there was an unusual logistical problem to be worked out. This was in stark\ncontrast to the much longer meetings with non-professional clients. " Based on this evidence I feel that Malawi\'s having a specific event planner would make them more efficent and help them have a better experience in their event planning because only half of the events are professional planners.\n\nCEO: I understand your reasoning for wanting to bring in an event planner, drawing from the description of Dan Evans\' extensive involvement and the distinction between professional and non-professional clients. You\'ve identified a clear bottleneck and a significant time sink for Dan.\n\nHowever, the case also states that "Malawi\'s had been offering catering service since they opened in 2010. In fact, they purchased a mobile oven even before they had a kitchen in their restaurant." It also mentions that "Malawi\'s did not have a staff that was dedicated to catering functions, but used the regular restaurant employees, most of whom worked part-time."\n\nGiven this information, how would you justify hiring a dedicated event planner for catering when the current model relies on existing restaurant staff and Dan Evans, and the business has only been handling about ten events per year? What specific evidence from the case supports the idea that adding a new, dedicated role is the *best* solution for scaling, rather than optimizing the existing processes or Dan\'s involvement?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I liked how kent kind of fought back with me and challenged my ideas.. I thought it was good to have to defend my point of view and give specific evidence\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: I think that if there were some more creative questions it could be helpful!\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yep!\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
