"score":4,"feedback":"After a somewhat generalized initial justification, Cole significantly improved his ability to connect his answers directly to the case. He effectively used information about catering\'s profitability, its inconsistent nature, Dan Evans\'s specific workload, and the goal of franchising to justify his evolving recommendations. This showed a strong capacity to apply case details to strategic decision-making.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','leading',0,4,'Helps me know small details of the case','Less agreeable','gemini-2.5-flash-lite','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Hi Kent, after much research I beleive that should not do catering anymore. At the end of the day we need to specicalize in one thing and we need to pick one or the other. Central restuarant operations and putting cpaital into that are going to be much more important than trying to focus on two things\n\nCEO: That\'s a very interesting perspective, STUDENT! Focusing on specialization and strengthening our core restaurant operations is certainly a valid strategic consideration. You\'re right, specialization can lead to excellence.\n\nHowever, the case does mention that catering is the "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." What are your thoughts on that fact when considering your recommendation to discontinue catering? How do you reconcile the profitability of catering with your desire for specialization?\n\nSTUDENT: It is the most portiable right now, and when we have evenrts. the thing about catering is it is an inconisstnet business compared ot having a brick and mortar restuarant running. If we put more focus into restuarant operations, profits would also be able to increase\n\nCEO: That\'s a sharp observation, STUDENT. You\'ve hit on a key point: the inconsistency of catering demand. It\'s true that a brick-and-mortar restaurant offers a more predictable revenue stream.\n\nYou\'ve also highlighted that catering is "inconsistent." The case does mention that Malawis was catering about ten events per year, mostly in the summer months. How do you think this seasonality and inconsistency might impact our ability to franchise the business, which is a major goal for us?\n\nSTUDENT: Well if we take out catering we dont need to worry about it and we would be able to franchise as normal\n\nCEO: That\'s a very direct approach, STUDENT. Removing catering would certainly simplify the franchising model by eliminating that variable.\n\nHowever, the case also states that catering is a significant driver of brand awareness, with attendees at events essentially "taste testing" our pizza. If we discontinue catering, how do you propose we replace that valuable word-of-mouth marketing and brand exposure, especially since the case mentions we do almost no advertising?\n\nSTUDENT: Idk\n\nCEO: No problem at all, STUDENT. Let\'s think about this together. You\'re right, it\'s a significant challenge to replace that kind of organic marketing.\n\nThe case mentions that catering events bring in hundreds of attendees and that people often choose Malawi\'s for catering based on attending a previous event or a recommendation. This suggests that the *experience* at a catered event is a powerful marketing tool.\n\nGiven that, if we were to *continue* with catering, how might we leverage that attendee experience to *improve* our brand awareness, rather than eliminate it? What aspects of the catering experience, as described in the case, could be further amplified to serve as marketing for the restaurants?\n\nSTUDENT: Ok lets change up, most ofo ur events are done in the summer and we can hire seaosnal wokers ot keep it going in busy months and not waste captial doing it the other 8/9 months of the year\n\nCEO: That\'s a fantastic idea, STUDENT! Hiring seasonal workers is a brilliant way to manage the fluctuating demand and control costs, especially during those peak summer months. It shows you\'re thinking practically about resource allocation.\n\nNow, let\'s dig a little deeper into the operational side. The case mentions that Dan Evans spends a significant amount of time, anywhere from 3 to 10 hours, planning events with clients, especially those who aren\'t professional event planners. How would your plan to hire seasonal workers address this reliance on Dan Evans and his time for event planning and execution?\n\nSTUDENT: We will have workers on standby, we can pay a littler bit more as catering is more profitable\n\nCEO: That\'s a good thought, STUDENT. Having workers on standby is definitely part of the solution. And you\'re absolutely right, the higher profitability of catering does give us some flexibility to invest a bit more in staffing.\n\nHowever, the case specifically points out that Dan Evans\'s involvement in planning can take *hours* per client, and it relies on his personal "intuition, experience, and knowledge." Simply having more staff on standby doesn\'t directly address the *planning bottleneck* that Dan represents. How can we ensure that the planning process itself becomes more efficient and less dependent on one individual, especially if we want to franchise this operation? What does the case suggest might be ways to streamline that client interaction?\n\nSTUDENT: If it is just one person on planning, lets make sure multiple people who are good as event planning are able to be on standby to plan these events. Somebdouy who understands the operatiosn behind cartering\n\nCEO: That\'s a very positive step, STUDENT! Training multiple people to handle event planning is a great idea for redundancy and skill-building. It definitely moves us away from relying solely on Dan.\n\nThe case mentions that Dan enjoys having "as much direct interaction with the client as possible" to ensure they feel attended to. While having multiple planners is good, the *process* of planning itself can still be very time-consuming. The case also notes that professional event planners are "fast and efficient" because they understand the industry.\n\nHow could we potentially adapt our process to be more efficient, perhaps by providing clients with more self-service options or standardized information, similar to how professional planners operate, without losing that personal touch that makes our catering special? Are there any tools or methods mentioned in the case that could help with this?\n\nSTUDENT: Sacrifices might need to be made to have a little less interaction. Maybe Dan can stop in for an hour or whatever spare time he has to make sure the customer knows he cares and is taken care of. Human interactions from malawis is still there. At the end of the day more demand is going to come and dan is one man\n\nCEO: You\'re absolutely right, STUDENT. Dan is one man, and the demand is growing. Making some adjustments to the level of interaction is likely necessary to scale. I appreciate you recognizing that a degree of sacrifice in the hyper-personalized interaction might be needed.\n\nThe case does suggest a few ways to streamline the planning process. For instance, it mentions the idea of a website for learning about options and requesting engagements, and also an "engagement information form" that clients could fill out. How might these tools help reduce Dan\'s planning time while still allowing for human interaction and ensuring client needs are met?\n\nSTUDENT: Time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Grea