INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('514a9e8f-d156-42e8-bee9-885b256a55c3','2025-10-27 16:03:50','8a071870-50b1-4396-8c88-00ed9225f942',13,'Jackson displayed excellent analytical and strategic thinking throughout the conversation. While there was a slight misstep in the initial assessment of the catering business, Jackson quickly demonstrated a strong ability to adapt, learn, and apply case information effectively. The proposed solutions for scaling the catering operation, including detailed strategies for quality control and a sophisticated understanding of financial implications, were particularly impressive. Jackson\'s ability to identify the core problem (Evans as a bottleneck) and offer actionable, well-justified solutions makes for a very strong performance.','[{"score":4,"feedback":"Jackson initially provided an answer that seemed to overlook the stated profitability of the catering business. However, after the CEO\'s prompt, Jackson quickly course-corrected, demonstrating a solid understanding of the case details, including Dan Evans\'s integral role, the mention of PCN analysis, and the broader context of franchising. This pivot showed a strong grasp of the material, indicating that the initial misstep was more about quick judgment than a lack of study.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"Jackson\'s initial answer was somewhat weak, but their subsequent responses were excellent. The detailed pivot to identify Dan Evans as a bottleneck, the proposed solutions of a dedicated salesperson and tiered services, the robust quality control measures (Product, Process, and Expectation Management), and the insightful financial analysis (High Margin/Low Volume to Sustainable Margin/High Volume) were all very strong and well-articulated. This demonstrates a high level of critical thinking and problem-solving.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":5,"feedback":"Jackson consistently justified their answers by drawing on relevant information from the case. They explicitly referenced the catering\'s profitability, Dan Evans\'s time commitment, the concept of a catering salesperson mentioned in the case, Jane Goodman\'s self-catering request, and the broader goals of franchising and PCN analysis. This strong integration of case facts significantly bolstered the credibility and depth of their recommendations.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','leading',0,3.56985,'idk','probably','gemini-2.5-flash-lite','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: We need to stay with our core restaurant operations. This catering business is a big distraction\n\nCEO: That\'s a very direct assessment, STUDENT. I appreciate your focus on our core restaurant operations. You\'ve identified a potential distraction, which is a valid concern for any business.\n\nHowever, the case does mention that catering is the "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." How do you reconcile that significant profitability with your recommendation to move away from it?\n\nSTUDENT: with the time we are wasting with the catering business we could be making more profits on the regular operations\n\nCEO: That\'s an interesting perspective, STUDENT. You\'re suggesting that the time and resources currently allocated to catering could be better utilized to enhance our core restaurant operations and, in turn, generate more profit. I can see the logic in wanting to maximize efficiency in our primary business.\n\nNow, thinking about the details in the case, it states that Dan Evans spends a significant amount of time, "anywhere between 3 and 10 hours depending on the client\'s needs," on planning catering events. How does this intensive involvement of Dan Evans impact your view on whether catering is truly a "distraction" or if there might be a way to make it more efficient?\n\nSTUDENT: i change my mind The problem is not the catering business itself, as it is profitable and a great marketing tool. The problem is the current highly customized and Evans-dependent process.\n\nThe path forward is to restructure the catering process to remove Evans as the bottleneck:\n\nHire a Dedicated Sales/Coordination Person: As suggested in the case, hiring a part-time catering salesperson would immediately free up Evans\'s 30 to 100 hours of planning time per year. This person would handle all initial client contact, documentation, menu, and standardized quoting.\n\nImplement Tiered/Standardized Services: By introducing "Drop-Off" or "Self-Catering" options (as detailed in the PCN analysis) with simple, fixed pricing, 80% of catering inquiries can be moved to a low-interaction model that requires minimal time from the GM.\n\nConclusion:\n\nCatering is a high-margin asset that provides effective synergy for the franchise model. Your concern that it\'s a distraction is valid under the current process. The goal is not to eliminate catering, but to professionalize it so that Evans is only involved in the highest-level strategy and troubleshooting, not the day-to-day execution.\n\nCEO: That\'s a fantastic pivot, STUDENT! You\'ve clearly identified the core issue: the current catering process is inefficient and overly reliant on Dan Evans, but the business itself holds significant potential. I love your idea of restructuring the process.\n\nHiring a dedicated sales/coordination person is a brilliant thought. You\'re right, that would immediately alleviate a huge burden on Dan. And the concept of tiered, standardized services  like "Drop-Off" or "Self-Catering"  is exactly the kind of innovative thinking we need. It addresses the need for efficiency while still leveraging the profitability of catering.\n\nYou\'ve really zeroed in on how to make this work. Now, let\'s dig a little deeper into those standardized services. The case mentions Jane Goodman\'s request for par-cooked pizzas for a self-catered event, and Dan\'s concern about brand image if quality suffers. How would you ensure that these new, lower-interaction catering options, like the "Self-Catering" model you proposed, maintain Malawi\'s high-quality image and brand reputation?\n\nSTUDENT: Your plan for maintaining our brand quality while offering new services is sound. We will implement three key controls: **Product Control** will involve standardizing the par-cook level of the crust and ensuring all delicate, fresh toppings are packaged separately to be added *after* the pizza is out of the oven, guaranteeing the final presentation meets our standards. **Process Control** will require us to provide simple, visual, step-by-step instructions with all DIY kitsand mandate proper equipmentto minimize user error at the venue. Finally, **Expectation Management** is crucial: our dedicated salesperson will clearly communicate the differences between our **Full-Service**, **Hot-Hold Delivery**, and **DIY Rental** tiers upfront, ensuring every client understands exactly what they are getting and that final quality in the DIY model depends on following our instructions, thereby protecting the Malawi\'s reputation while we successfully scale.\n\nCEO: Excellent, STUDENT! Product Control, Process Control, and Expectation Management  those are three very strong pillars for ensuring quality. I particularly like how you\'ve thought about the visual instructions for the DIY kits and the clear communication from the salesperson. That proactive approach to managing client expectations is exactly what we need.\n\nYou\'ve presented a compelling strategy for scaling our catering operation while maintaining our brand\'s reputation. It addresses the profitability, the operational bottleneck, and the need for standardization for franchising.\n\nNow, let\'s consider the financial implications. The case states that catering is our "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." If we successfully implement these standardized tiers, how do you anticipate the *profitability* of these new, lower-interaction catering options will compare to our current, more hands-on catering model?\n\nSTUDENT: The shift to standardized catering tiers will change our financial profile from a **"High Margin/Low Volume"** model to a **"Sustainable Margin/High Volume"** model. While the **gross profit margin percentage (%)** for new options like Drop-Off or DIY will be **lower** than our current premium full-service modelas we eliminate the high gratuity and charge a lower service pricethe **total aggregate profit** will be significantly higher. This is because these new, low-interaction models drastically **reduce our variable labor costs** and, crucially, **remove Dan Evans as a bottleneck.** This allows us to handle many more events per month, generating a much higher **profit per hour** for our limited managerial time, ultimately leading to greater overall dollar profits and a more financially attractive, replicable system for future franchising.\n\nCEO: That\'s a very insightful financial analysis, STUDENT. You\'ve clearly articulated the shift from "High Margin/Low Volume" to "Sustainable Margin/High Volume," and you\'ve correctly identified that while the *percentage* margin might decrease on the new tiers, the *total aggregate profit* will increase due to reduced labor costs and increased volume. That\'s a critical distinction.\n\nYou\'ve done a great job of laying out a strategic path forward for our catering business. You\'ve identified the problems, proposed solutions, and considered the quality and financial implications.\n\nAt this point, I think we\'ve had a very productive discussion. If it is time to conclude this conversation you need to say the phrase \'time is up\'.\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: sure\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 3.5698456\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: idk\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: probably\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: no\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
