e are excellent, actionable ideas! Implementing tiered catering packages is a brilliant way to bring predictability to pricing and offerings, which is crucial for franchising. And the Client Logistics Checklist and Operations Manual  that\'s exactly the kind of detail we need to ensure consistency.\n\nYou\'ve also identified the need for dedicated roles: a Catering Sales Coordinator and an On-Site Catering Lead. This directly addresses the scalability issue.\n\nNow, let\'s dig a bit deeper into the "Standardization" point. You suggested stopping custom, on-the-fly quotes. The case mentions that Dan Evans "would calculate the per-plate price on the fly" and that he was "happy to work with budgets, always taking time to come up with alternative menus that would fit within the client\'s budget constraint."\n\nHow do you propose we handle clients who might still have specific budget needs or unique requests that fall outside of these standardized packages, without losing that premium, customized feel that our catering clients expect?\n\nSTUDENT: Great question, I think it would be important to make sure that there is a package for every core customer that we have. If we are constantly getting customers that can\'t afford our packages, we should reevaluate and create cheaper packages.\n\nCEO: That\'s a very practical approach, STUDENT. Re-evaluating and creating new packages based on customer feedback and affordability is a smart move. It shows we\'re listening to the market.\n\nHowever, the case also mentions that catering clients are "less price sensitive" because they are catering special events. We also see that Dan Evans\'s current pricing model includes a $100 catering fee, a per-plate price between $8-$12, and a 19% gratuity. He also notes that "the larger the event, the lower they were able to go with the price per plate."\n\nHow would your tiered package system account for the flexibility in pricing based on event size, and how can we ensure these packages still