ze the consulting that Dan is currently doing\n\nCEO: That\'s a good thought, STUDENT. Providing clients with planning resources could streamline the process. However, the case specifically mentions that the time Evans spends with clients can range from "3 to 10 hours depending on the clients needs."\n\nHow would a manual, even a detailed one, fully address the unique needs and questions of a non-professional event planner who might require that level of personalized guidance, and what specific details from the case would support your belief that a manual alone is sufficient?\n\nSTUDENT: I don\'t necessarily think that manuals alone are sufficient. By increasing year-round business we can justify hiring staff specific to the catering field, freeing up leaders like Evans. These staff could also make bonuses for giving extra time to helping clients, and clients could pay premiums for specialized consulting services\n\nCEO: Hiring dedicated catering staff and offering premium consulting services are indeed potential solutions to reduce Evans\'s burden. However, the case also points out that "Malawis had been offering catering service since they opened in 2010... Malawi\'s was catering about ten events per year, mostly in the summer months with one or two in the winter."\n\nGiven this low volume of events, how can we justify the cost of hiring dedicated catering staff and offering specialized consulting services when the current demand doesn\'t seem to support it? Where in the case does it suggest we can generate enough business to sustain these new roles?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? 