ns\'s central, time-consuming role. They also acknowledged the challenge of transferring \'intuition, experience, and knowledge\' as discussed in the case, showing a good connection between their proposed solutions and the case\'s details.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','liberal',0,5,'It gave me real life questions to think through','sometimes the process was repetative','gemini-2.5-flash-lite','gemini-2.5-flash','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes you should\n\nCEO: That\'s a direct answer, STUDENT. I appreciate that. Now, tell me, **what specifically in the case leads you to believe we should continue with catering?** What makes it so compelling that we should pour our resources into it?\n\nSTUDENT: Catering is very profitable and working well, with changes like standardization and employee improvements and better training the process will only improve\n\nCEO: I\'m glad to hear you\'ve identified the profitability of catering. The case does state it\'s our "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." However, you also mentioned "changes like standardization and employee improvements and better training." **Can you elaborate on what specific operational challenges the case highlights that these changes would address?**\n\nSTUDENT: Standardize the Process:\n\nCreate detailed catering packages (menu, pricing, service levels) instead of custom quotes for every event.\n\nDevelop training manuals and checklists for setup, cooking, and cleanup.\n\nDelegate and Train Staff:\n\nTrain assistant managers or dedicated catering coordinators to handle client interactions and event execution.\n\nThis would free Evans from being the single point of contact.\n\nExpand Equipment Capacity:\n\nAdd another mobile oven or trailer setup to allow multiple events at once.\n\nThis increases revenue potential without sacrificing quality.\n\nIntegrate with Franchising:\n\nOffer the catering model as an optional revenue stream for franchisees.\n\nProvide a standardized catering kit with equipment, procedures, and marketing materials.\n\nSimplify Customer Options:\n\nOffer tiered service models:\n\nFull-Service Catering (on-site cooking, premium price)\n\nDrop-Off Catering (par-baked pizzas, simpler logistics, lower price)\n\nCEO: Those are some solid ideas, STUDENT. You\'ve clearly put thought into how to address the operational inefficiencies. You mentioned standardizing processes and training staff to reduce reliance on Dan Evans. **Can you point to any specific examples in the case that illustrate the burden on Dan Evans and why this standardization and delegation is so crucial?**\n\nSTUDENT: He handles almost everything by himself, in the case it discusses that he handles all logistics on his own, he is the main point of contact, and he cooks all the pizzas by himself while the staff is serving,\n\nCEO: You\'re right that Dan Evans is heavily involved, and the case does highlight his extensive role. However, let\'s look a bit closer. The case states, "The main exception was the time Evans would spend with the client planning the event, which could take anywhere between 3 and 10 hours depending on the clients needs." It also mentions that he "manned the oven and would cook four pizzas at a time." **Does this suggest he\'s doing *everything* himself, or are there other employees involved in the process? And if so, what does that imply about the scalability of his current role?**\n\nSTUDENT: There are employees obviously involved in other areas, but the main line is on his shoulders. His role is vital and without him the operations could hardly function. Training of other employees can allow his burden to be lightened.\n\nCEO: That\'s a