hise? What specific facts from the case support your proposed solutions?\n\nSTUDENT: The numbers show we can make lots of money\n\nCEO: You\'re right that the case does point to catering\'s profitability. It\'s described as "the most profitable part of the restaurant operation." That\'s a strong financial incentive.\n\nHowever, simply stating that it\'s profitable doesn\'t address the operational challenges we just discussed. If we want to scale this profitable venture, especially with franchising in mind, how do we move past the current model that is so dependent on Dan Evans\'s personal time and expertise? What specific actions can we take, drawing from the case, to make this operation more replicable and less reliant on one individual?\n\nSTUDENT: \'times up\'\n\nCEO: If it is time to conclude this conversation you need to say the phrase \'time is up\'\n\nSTUDENT: \'time is up\'\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: good conversation.\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: Simple questions\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. 