p Evans\'s time and the desire to scale by hiring more people. However, the case details the extensive time Evans currently spends with clients, often acting as an event planner. How would a new hire, or even more staff, directly address the core issue of Evans\'s personal involvement and expertise being critical to the current planning process, especially if we\'re aiming for a franchise model?\n\nSTUDENT: We can create technological systems to do the parts of cost estimation. We can create a standardized menu for catering. We can create more strict rules for the types of events we will cater to or not. For a franchise model, we as the franchise owner can give the option for the franchisee to buy ovens from us.\n\nCEO: You\'re touching on some interesting ideas there, STUDENT. Let\'s unpack them. You mentioned creating "technological systems to do the parts of cost estimation" and a "standardized menu." Where in the case do you see evidence that suggests these types of solutions would be effective or feasible for our catering operation?\n\nSTUDENT: I see that a lot of the time taken for the catering is deciding the prices and figuring out how to uniquely meet the customers needs. If we can streamline this, the value we get compared to the time and money investment becomes higher.\n\nCEO: I understand your thinking about streamlining the process to increase the value proposition. However, the case describes Dan Evans as pricing every event himself, "on the fly," based on COGS, labor, and margin. It also mentions his preference for extensive personal interaction to set client expectations and customize menus.\n\nGiven this, how would a standardized menu and technological cost estimation directly address the significant amount of direct, personalized interaction and customized menu planning that Evans currently handles, especially for non-professional event planners who require considerable guidance?\n\nSTUDENT: Our catering can focus on the high quality food as our core competency (just as it is for our normal business) rather than the personalization.\n\nCEO: Focusing on high-quality food as our core competency is certainly a strong point for Malawi\'s. However, the case states that Dan Evans spends anywhere from 3 to 10 hours with clients, often acting as an event planner, and that clients are paying a premium for this "customized service."\n\nIf we shift away from personalization to focus solely on high-quality food with a standardized menu, how do you propose we justify the premium pricing and maintain client satisfaction, particularly with those non-professional event planners who seem to rely heavily on that personalized guidance and customization?\n\nSTUDENT: Customers will pay a premium service because we will have high quality food and we will be professional, on time, and deliver their needs of having great food. Customers don\'t want to have to invest so much time into the catering for their event either, so streamlining the process will be beneficial for them as well. We may not have quite the premium price because our service isn\'t as customized, but because we invest less time into the service, it still gives us the same or higher margins\n\nCEO: You\'re making a compelling argument for efficiency and maintaining profitability through a standardized, high-quality offering. You\'ve referenced the premium pricing, the time investment from clients, and the potential for higher margins due to reduced personal interaction.\n\nNow, let\'s pivot to implementation. You\'ve convinced me that there\'s a viable path forward by standardizing the catering offering. However, the case clearly states that the entire catering operation hinges on Dan Evans\'s "intuition, experience, and knowledge." He\'s the bottleneck. How do you propose we overcome this dependency on Dan Evans to ensure scalability and replicability, especially with our ultimate goal of franchising?\n\nSTUDENT: create standard operating procedures\n\nCEO: Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) are a good start, STUDENT. But the case highlights that Dan Evans\'s role involves a significant amount of subjective judgment and client-specific problem-solving  from menu customization to navigating unique venue access issues.\n\nHow would you design SOPs that can effectively capture and transfer Dan\'s "intuition, experience, and knowledge" to others, ensuring consistent quality and client satisfaction across different events and potentially different franchisees, without him being directly involved in every single catering engagement?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: it made me think\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: it was great\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),