using relevant reading information?"}]','strict',1,NULL,NULL,NULL,'gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash-lite','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: I think that we can expand it and standardize catering operations that way it doesn\'t just rely on your personal expertise\n\nCEO: Expand it? STUDENT, the case states we\'re only doing about ten events a year, and it\'s taking Dan Evans up to 10 hours of planning for a single client. That seems like a massive time sink for a very small part of our business.\n\nWhy should we double down on catering when our core restaurant is growing so well?\n\nSTUDENT: Thats a fair concern, Mr. Beck  and youre right, ten events a year for that much prep time isnt sustainable in its current form. Right now, catering is profitable but inefficient. Its not about doubling down on the current process  its about transforming it into a scalable, systemized revenue stream.\n\nThe catering side already shows strong margins and customer conversion  it exposes new audiences to Malawis mission and often drives repeat visits to the restaurants. Instead of dropping it entirely, we can protect the restaurants focus while redesigning catering operations to make it efficient and replicable.\n\nSpecifically, we could:\n\nStandardize the process through a Catering Operations Manual so Dans ten hours of prep becomes one or two.\n\nTrain other team members or franchise partners to manage events using the same proven model.\n\nDigitize planning with online ordering and preset catering packages, reducing custom workload.\n\nThis keeps catering aligned with your core mission  feeding people and doing good  without draining your top talent. The restaurant stays the focus, but catering becomes a low-effort, high-margin complement that strengthens brand reach.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, you\'re proposing we create new manuals and digital tools. That sounds like a lot of work and investment.\n\nThat\'s an interesting set of recommendations, but where in the case does it support building all that new infrastructure? You mentioned \'strong margins.\' Let\'s be precise. What does the case actually say about the profitability of our catering operation?\n\nSTUDENT: Thats a fair question, Mr. Beck  and youre right to ask for specifics.\n\nAccording to the case, while catering only accounts for around ten events a year, each event is highly profitable, with gross margins well above the restaurant average. Thats mainly because catering leverages bulk food preparation, which lowers per-unit food costs, and requires fewer labor hours per dollar of revenue compared to restaurant service. On top of that, marketing costs are virtually zero  most clients come through referrals or existing relationships.\n\nSo even though the volume is low, each event produces a large transaction size and strong per-event profit, making catering one of Malawis most profitable activities on a percentage basis. The challenge isnt the margins  its scalability. The case notes that Dan Evans spends about 10 hours of planning per client, and that dependence on his personal effort keeps the program from growing.\n\nMy recommendation isnt to invest heavily in new infrastructure, but to document and standardize whats already working profitably  perhaps by creating a simple catering playbook and training staff to share that workload. That small investment would turn a high-margin but time-consuming operation into something that can grow without distracting from restaurant performance.\n\nCEO: Alright, STUDENT. You\'ve made your point. The case does state that catering is our "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." You\'re right to focus on that.\n\nSo, you\'ve convinced me of the value. Now, let\'s talk about the \'how\'. The entire process depends on Dan Evans\'s "intuition, experience, and knowledge." That\'s not a system; that\'s one guy.\n\nHow, specifically, do we solve this reliance on Evans so that any franchisee in another city can replicate our success?\n\nSTUDENT: give me a hint\n\nCEO: Okay, STUDENT, I can give you a hint. This is your one free hint; any more will cost you a point.\n\nThink about *why* Evans spends so much time with clients. The case mentions two different types of clients he deals with. What\'s the key difference between them, and what does that tell you about the tasks that are taking up most of his time? Breaking down his process might reveal parts that don\'t actually require his unique culinary expertise.\n\nSTUDENT: Thats a great point, Mr. Beck  and youre absolutely right that the catering process isnt scalable right now because it lives entirely in Dan Evanss head.\n\nThe case gives us a critical clue as to why he spends so much time with each client. It describes two very different types of catering customers: repeat corporate clients and one-time special-event clients  weddings, fundraisers, and community events.\n\nThe corporate clients are consistent and predictable; they usually want standardized menus, simple logistics, and recurring orders. Those jobs dont need Dans culinary creativity or personal touch  they just need a clear system that someone else can follow.\n\nBut the one-time clients, like weddings or large community functions, often expect custom menus and high-touch service  and thats where Dans experience, intuition, and personal involvement really add value.\n\nWhat this tells us is that Dans time is being spent across two very different types of work  some that require his expertise and some that dont. The solution isnt to pull him out completely, but to separate and streamline:\n\nSystematize the repeatable work. Create standardized menus, pricing, and planning templates for corporate clients so any trained manager can execute those events with minimal oversight.\n\nPreserve the premium work. Keep Dans personal involvement for high-profile, one-time clients where customization enhances brand reputation and justifies his time.\n\nCodify and train. Document Dans approach into a simple playbook and train franchisees to handle Tier 1 (corporate) events independently, while reserving Tier 2 (custom) events for more experienced managers.\n\nThis way, were not trying to replace Dan  were designing a process that protects his creative value while scaling the repeatable, profitable side of catering that doesnt need his direct attention.\n\nCEO: Okay, STUDENT, that\'s a sharp analysis. Differentiating between client types is a good start.\n\nBut your \'systematized\' approach seems to solve for the easy clientsthe professional planners who are already efficient. The case states the real time-drain is the non-professionals. Evans says he feels like he\'s "planning the whole event instead of only catering it."\n\nHow does a standardized playbook for a franchisee in Arizona solve the problem of a client who needs that level of hand-holding and is asking for free event planning advice?\n\nSTUDENT: Thats a very fair concern, Mr. Beck  and youre absolutely right. The case is clear that the biggest time drain isnt our professional clients, its the non-professional planners  individuals planning weddings or charity events who lean on Dan for end-to-end coordination. He even says, I feel like Im planning the whole event instead of only catering it.\n\nA playbook alone doesnt fix that. What we really need is to redefine the boundaries of our service and build structure around how we handle these clients. Heres what Id propose:\n\n1. Create clear service tiers.\nWe formalize two levels of catering service:\n\nA Standard Package for corporate and repeat clients  straightforward menus, preset pricing, and minimal planning.\n\nA Premium Event Package for non-professional or custom clients, which includes optional event-planning assistance for an additional fee.\nThis lets us meet client needs without giving away Dans time for free.\n\n2. Build a referral network instead of doing it all ourselves.\nFor clients who truly need event planning, we can partner with local planners or venues and refer them as part of a bundled experience. Franchisees can do the same in their markets  it keeps us focused on food, not florists.\n\n3. Train staff to triage client needs.\nThe playbook then serves as a guide for franchisees and managers to identify which clients require high-touch service, and how to manage those relationships efficiently.\n\nThe point isnt to automate empathy  its to set clear boundaries and capture value for the extra work were already doing. Thats how a franchisee in Arizona could offer the same personal touch Dan provides, but in a structured, profitable way.\n\nCEO: Charging for the extra work is an interesting thought, STUDENT. It directly addresses the problem of Evans giving away free consulting.\n\nBut it makes me think of the Jane Goodman situation. Evans was worried that letting her self-cater with our par-cooked pizzas would damage the Malawi\'s brand if the quality suffered.\n\nHow is your proposed \'Standard Package\' any different? Aren\'t we risking our high-quality, high-touch image by offering a less customized, potentially lower-quality experience?\n\nSTUDENT: Thats a great point, Mr. Beck  and I agree that brand integrity is non-negotiable. The Jane Goodman case proves that if we hand over too much control, we risk inconsistent quality and damage to the Malawis reputation.\n\nThe difference with my Standard Package proposal is that it doesnt lower standards  it simplifies execution. Were not asking clients to self-cater or handle the food themselves, as in Goodmans case. Instead, were offering a tightly controlled, pre-designed catering option that our staff still prepares, delivers, and serves under Malawis supervision.\n\nThink of it as a franchise-ready catering model: fewer variables, same quality. Each menu item, packaging method, and presentation style would be tested and standardized by us. That means a franchisee in Arizona can replicate the same customer experience Dan provides in Utah  the same food, same warmth, same service, just with less custom planning time.\n\nFor those high-profile, high-touch events where personalization defines the brand, we keep that as our Premium Package  handled by more experienced staff who can deliver that elevated experience without compromising quality.\n\nIn short, the Standard Package simplifies logistics, not standards. It protects the Malawis brand by ensuring that every event, whether simple or custom, still meets our quality and service promise  just with the right level of effort for the right type of client.\n\nCEO: Okay, STUDENT, that\'s a crucial distinction. You\'re right that simplifying the menu options isn\'t the same as letting a customer cook our food. Maintaining control over the execution is key to protecting the brand.\n\nBut a playbook and standardized menus solve planning issues. What about the day-of execution problems? The case mentions multiple times that our team arrives at a venue only to find they can\'t park the truck or that the driveway is too narrow for the oven trailer. It\'s embarrassing and stressful.\n\nHow does your new, standardized process prevent those kinds of logistical nightmares from happening?\n\nSTUDENT: Youre absolutely right, Mr. Beck. The case describes those on-site disasters  like the team showing up to find theres nowhere to park or no power hookup  as some of the most stressful and embarrassing moments for staff. Those arent food problems; theyre information problems.\n\nThe standardized playbook Im proposing doesnt just cover menu options  it also builds in logistical checkpoints to prevent exactly those issues. Heres how:\n\n1. Pre-Event Site Verification Checklist.\nEvery event  corporate or special  would require the client to complete a short site survey form or virtual walkthrough. It covers basics like truck clearance, parking access, distance to kitchen area, and available power. This takes 10 minutes but prevents hours of chaos later.\n\n2. Internal Go/No-Go Logistics Review.\nBefore committing, a manager reviews the site details and signs off that its feasible with our equipment. If not, we propose alternate setups  like using our mobile oven on a smaller trailer or adjusting menu items.\n\n3. Centralized Event-Tracking Sheet.\nFranchisees or managers log every event with notes on access issues and lessons learned. Over time, this builds an internal database  a living guide that helps future teams anticipate problems before they happen.\n\nSo instead of relying on Dans intuition  Hes been doing it long enough to know which venues work  were codifying that intuition into a system. Its simple, repeatable, and protects both the teams confidence and the brands reliability.\n\nCEO: A pre-event checklist... that\'s a sharp, practical solution, STUDENT. That directly addresses the kind of on-site surprises that make us look unprofessional. It turns reactive problem-solving into a proactive, repeatable system. I like that.\n\nYou\'ve laid out a solid plan for fixing and standardizing our current catering model. But the case mentions other ideas that have come up organicallycustomers asking to rent the oven, or the self-catering model Jane Goodman proposed.\n\nShould we pursue these other models as part of our franchise offering, or are they just another distraction from our core business?\n\nSTUDENT: we should pursue these models\n\nCEO: Pursue them? STUDENT, that seems to add a lot of complexity when we\'re trying to standardize.\n\nLet\'s focus on the self-catering idea for a moment. The case is very clear about Evans\'s concern with Jane Goodman: if the pizzas were not heated properly, the quality might suffer and reflect poorly on our brand.\n\nHow do you propose we sell par-cooked pizzas to customers without losing complete control over the quality of the final product and risking our reputation?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: I cant\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
