ed so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Yes, we should stay in the catering business as the case reveals that catering is the most profitable part of our restaurant operation. It is profitable because it gets the brand out there, provides high margins, and low overhead. However the way we approach catering need to be reframed because it is currently very labor intensive and structured in a  way that creates a stressful bottleneck in operations. These pain points are addressable so we should not give up on the initiative entirely until those have been addressed.\n\nCEO: You\'ve identified the core tension, STUDENT. You say it\'s profitable, but you also say it\'s a "stressful bottleneck."\n\nThe case mentions Dan Evans can spend between 3 and 10 hours planning a single event. That\'s a huge time commitment for my General Manager. How can we call this a high-margin business when my most skilled manager is spending that much unbilled time just on planning?\n\nSTUDENT: Youre right. Dan spending up to 10 hours planning one event definitely cuts into the margins. I dont think that means catering isnt profitable though, it just means the process isnt scalable yet. Right now it relies too much on his personal touch.\n\nIf we document and standardize how those events are planned, like using preset menu options, pricing templates, or offering simpler tiers such as a drop-off option, we can cut that planning time way down. I would also look at training another employee to handle the front-end logistics so Dan can focus on quality and operations.\n\nCatering can stay high-margin. We just need to structure it so the time and effort match the return.\n\nCEO: Standardization and templates... that sounds efficient.\n\nBut the case says Evans believes we command premium pricing precisely *because* we offer "the highest degree of attention and customizati