 on Dan Evans and his personal expertise, which takes him up to 10 hours per client. That\'s not a scalable model for franchising.\n\nHow do you propose we fix that?\n\nSTUDENT: have dan train some other employees so they know what to dol\n\nCEO: Training is a good idea, STUDENT, but Dan\'s value isn\'t just procedural. He spends up to 10 hours with non-professional clients, essentially acting as a free event planner. That\'s a high-touch, consultative role that relies on his years of experience.\n\nHow do we standardize that \'intuition\' for a franchisee\'s new hire without losing the premium service our clients expect?\n\nSTUDENT: have the employee tag along and follow dan while he does that. Or just make that Dan\'s only role in the company and have someone else do his other responsibilities\n\nCEO: STUDENT, both of those ideas still make the entire operation dependent on one highly-skilled person. That\'s the opposite of a replicable franchise model. We can\'t clone Dan for every new location.\n\nThe problem isn\'t just *who* does the work, it\'s the *work itself*. Dan is spending hours acting as a free event planner for inexperienced clients.\n\nInstead of just throwing more people at the problem, how can we change the *process* to reduce the need for that 10-hour, hands-on consultation in the first place?\n\nSTUDENT: Great line of thought. Create an online form that the clients go through to help that narrows down what they like and what type of service they want. This will weed out a lot of unnecessary time. You can still maintain a person to person interaction following the form, but this will save a lot of time\n\nCEO: That\'s a sharp idea, STUDENT. An online form could definitely streamline the initial planning and gather key details efficiently, especially from those non-professional planners.\n\nBut planning is only half the battle. The case mentions several on-site disasters: backing the oven down a tiny, curved driveway, or showing up to find no place