 am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: Stay in the catering business\n\nCEO: Interesting. You\'re quick to decide.\n\nI\'m concerned, though. The case makes it clear that catering is extremely dependent on Dan Evans. It mentions his "intuition, experience, and knowledge" and that planning can take him up to 10 hours per client. That sounds like a major bottleneck, not a scalable business model ready for franchising.\n\nWhat facts from the case convince you that keeping the catering business is worth this operational headache?\n\nSTUDENT: What if you did a mix?\n\nCEO: "A mix"? That\'s a bit vague, STUDENT. A mix of what, exactly?\n\nBefore we start brainstorming solutions, you need to convince me it\'s a problem worth solving. You\'re sidestepping my main concern: the entire operation hinges on Dan Evans. That\'s not a business, it\'s a one-man show. Why should I invest more resources into something that isn\'t scalable or replicable for our franchisees?\n\nSTUDENT: do some training, and teach others how ot think like you as employees\n\nCEO: Training people to replicate the intuition of a seasoned chef is easier said than done, STUDENT. That\'s a significant investment.\n\nYou\'re jumping to solutions, but you haven\'t sold me on the fundamental premise. You still haven\'t answered my original question. Why is this catering business worth the headache? What specific facts in the case make you believe this is a golden opportunity we absolutely must pursue, despite the obvious operational burdens?\n\nSTUDENT: this catering business is a premise that franchises can expand but to be able to replicat the chefs expertise is hard. if you made a database with everything yoiu need to know would that be realiatic?\n\nCEO: Let\'s back up, STUDENT. A database, training... those are all potential solutions, and they all cost time and money.\n\nYou\'re trying to solve a problem you haven\'t yet convinced me is worth solving. You\'re asking me to invest in fixing the catering operation, but you haven\'t given me a single hard fact from the case to justify that investment.\n\nWhat does the case say about the financial contribution of the catering business that makes it worth all this trouble?\n\nSTUDENT: Let me justify it by telling you that it is worth it by telling your customers that they are worth it. Let me explain, if customers like ypotu prpduct they\'ll want to qccess it in more places than one. This will expand your profit and satisfy customers in multiple area.\n\nCEO: STUDENT, I appreciate the focus on the customer, and in a general sense, you\'re right. But "satisfying customers" doesn\'t pay the bills. We are running a business here, and I need a concrete business reason, a financial reason, to invest in solving these problems.\n\nYou\'re speaking in generalities. The case provides a very specific, powerful financial justification for keeping the catering business. What does the case explicitly state about the profitability of our catering operation?\n\nSTUDENT: The case explicitly states that Malawis catering is its most profitable operation, aligns with broader industry trends of higher margins than restaurant dining, and is considered a strategic area for growth and franchising.\n\nCEO: Exactly. That\'s the key point. The case states catering is the "most profitable part of the restaurant operation."\n\nGood, you\'ve clearly read the case. You\'ve convinced me it\'s worth the effort financially.\n\nNow, let\'s get practical. How do we solve the Dan Evans problem? The whole process relies on his personal intuition and can take up to 10 hours per client. We can\'t franchise Dan Evans. What\'s your first concrete step to standardize the planning process so we can replicate it?\n\nSTUDENT: document Evanss