elevant reading information?"}]','strict',0,4,'I like the thought provoking questions that tie me back to the case','asking me for evidence from teh case','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash-lite','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: We should stay in the catering business, because it is our most profitable offering to customers. It also strengthens our brand and reputation. We should just adjust our process in catering in order to streamline and expand it.\n\nCEO: That\'s an interesting take, STUDENT. You\'re right, the case does state that catering is our most profitable operation.\n\nBut I\'m concerned about the scalability. The case mentions Dan Evans spends between 3 and 10 hours planning each event, and the whole process relies on his personal expertise. That doesn\'t seem like a model we can replicate for a franchise. How do you propose we solve that problem?\n\nSTUDENT: We need to create training material to teach franchises how to replicate the catering process. We also need Dan Evans to train individuals at other locations how to move forward with catering. The case says that professional and non professional clients were largely different in their expectations. We need to also standardize our catering options to streamline the work we are doing--also making it more scaleable.\n\nCEO: You\'ve hit on a key point there, STUDENT, about the difference between professional and non-professional clients.\n\nBut let\'s focus on your idea of standardization. The case mentions that Evans often feels like he\'s "planning the whole event instead of only catering it" for non-professional clients. How would standardizing our options reduce the 3-10 hours of planning time he spends with them? It seems those clients need a lot of hand-holding, not a pre-set menu.\n\nSTUDENT: Having a clear explanation of what is included in each of the options can help, especially having that description online that they can study before meeting together. Having a clear plan for the event beforehand as a prerequisite could help a lot too.\n\nCEO: Okay, a more self-service approach. But the case states that Evans provides a "high degree of attention and customization," which is what justifies our premium pricing. If we standardize everything and push clients to a website, aren\'t we losing the very thing that makes our catering so valuable? How do you prevent that, STUDENT?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 4\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I like the thought provoking questions that tie me back to the case\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: asking me for evidence from teh case\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),s