INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('7d0172f2-19b8-442f-9bca-49616a1f7277','2025-10-27 19:03:59','fd4b56ba-1048-4582-aa45-b779b46df939',11,'Zach demonstrated a strong grasp of the case material and offered thoughtful, albeit not always fully developed, solutions. He correctly identified key profitability drivers and the challenges related to scaling the catering business for franchising. While some of his suggestions could be refined to better align with the goal of expansion, his overall approach was commendable, showing good analytical skills and a solid understanding of the business case.','[{"score":4,"feedback":"The student demonstrated a good understanding of the reading material, consistently referencing key points such as catering being the most profitable part of the business and Dan Evans\'s integral role. They also correctly recalled details about the company\'s history and other ventures like their work with Four Seasons and Ritz Carlton, indicating they had studied the case.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"The student provided decent answers that addressed the core of the CEO\'s questions. However, some answers, particularly regarding scaling and client management, could have been more robust. For instance, the suggestion to make clients fill out a survey as a qualifier seemed to contradict the goal of expanding business, and the response to the 10-hour planning session issue was a bit of a workaround rather than a fully scalable solution.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":4,"feedback":"The student did a good job of justifying their answers by drawing on information from the case. They correctly pointed to catering being the most profitable and mentioned Dan Evans\'s role. They also referenced the need for a replicable process for franchising, which is a key theme in the case. The justification for creating a flowchart was also well-linked to the need for a standardized system.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','liberal',0,3,'I liked how kent asked follow up questions, encouraging me to dig deeper on my analysis','kent could respond quicker','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash-lite','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes you should stay in the catering business\n\nCEO: Interesting, STUDENT. You\'re advocating we keep it.\n\nBut I\'m concerned about scalability. The case states that the entire catering process depends on Dan Evans\'s personal "intuition, experience, and knowledge." That\'s a huge bottleneck, especially since our main goal is to franchise.\n\nFrom a business perspective, why is it so important that we solve this problem instead of just cutting our losses and focusing on the core restaurant?\n\nSTUDENT: catering is the most profitable part of operations for Malawis, you could hire on another catering expert if you are concerned about Dan Evan\'s expertise, and/or draw from your previous work experience at Four Seasons and Ritz Carlton. It is important to solve this problem because if you don\'t, you will be cutting a huge profit driver for the company\n\nCEO: You\'re right, STUDENT, the case does state that catering is our most profitable operation. That\'s a crucial point.\n\nBut your solution of hiring another expert doesn\'t quite solve my core problem. Remember, our main goal is to franchise. We can\'t put a \'Dan Evans\' in every new location. We need a *system*, a replicable process that any competent manager can follow.\n\nSo, how would you propose we standardize what Dan does so that a franchisee in another state could successfully run a catering operation without him?\n\nSTUDENT: create a written operations flowchart that can be distributed to each manager at each location/franchise. essentially an in-depth if-then chart that guides managers at locations to make decisions that will promote growth within the franchise\n\nCEO: A flowchart is a good step toward creating a system. I like that.\n\nBut let\'s get specific. The case mentions Dan spends up to 10 hours with non-professional clients, essentially acting as their event planner. How can a flowchart replace that level of intense, personal interaction without making those clients feel lost or neglected?\n\nSTUDENT: the flowchart can address the most common issues/concerns that previous clients and Dan\'s non-professional clients have, and for more niche concerns that have never come up or have been addressed before, managers can call Dan or other executive leaders for expertise. when those niche problems are solved and worked through, those situations can then be added to the ever growing flowchart\n\nCEO: That\'s a decent idea for handling exceptions, STUDENT, but it doesn\'t solve the fundamental problem of the 10-hour planning sessions. We\'d still have managers calling Dan, which doesn\'t help us scale for franchising.\n\nThe case shows that professional planners are quick and easy. It\'s the non-professionals who need all the event planning help.\n\nSo, what tools could we give directly to the *clients* to make the planning process more self-service and efficient for them?\n\nSTUDENT: before we choose to accept their business, make the clients fill out a survey that acts as a qualifier, making sure that clients have situations and plans that roughly fit the previously standardized system. If their business will be too out of range, we can\'t accept them unless they change their requirements from what malawis provides\n\nCEO: That\'s one way to standardize, STUDENT, but it sounds like you\'re suggesting we turn away paying customers.\n\nRemember, the case mentions my goal is to *expand* the high-margin catering operation. How does turning away business help us achieve that goal?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 3\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: I liked how kent asked follow up questions, encouraging me to dig deeper on my analysis\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: kent could respond quicker\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('2e8772f2-1822-4cd0-80f5-9f90ebe13fda','2025-10-27 19:04:07','e82f6edf-78a8-4599-ab95-b83492e83ded',8,'Chloe demonstrated a basic understanding of the case, correctly identifying Malawi\'s Pizza\'s informal image and the appeal of its core product. However, she struggled to connect these points to the strategic nuances of the catering business, particularly regarding premium pricing and customer expectations for formal events. Further study of how customization drives profitability in the catering sector would be beneficial. She correctly identified that the catering business should align with the company\'s existing operations and image.','[{"score":3,"feedback":"The student\'s answers showed some understanding of the case, referencing aspects like the company\'s informal nature and the appeal of its pizza. However, they seemed to miss key details about the premium pricing strategy for catering and the role of customization in that segment, suggesting a partial understanding of the provided material.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"The student provided generally coherent answers but struggled to fully integrate the nuanced information from the case. While they correctly identified that Malwai\'s pizza is a draw, they underestimated the value placed on premium service in the catering context, which was a central point in the case. Their suggestion to remove elements of premium service for larger events, while simplifying operations, directly contradicted the case\'s explanation of why premium pricing is possible.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":2,"feedback":"The student made some attempts to justify their answers by referencing Malwai\'s informal image and the appeal of their pizza. However, they did not effectively draw upon the specific details in the reading material that explained the profitability of catering, the premium pricing strategy, and the importance of customization and attention for events like weddings. The justification was superficial and did not deeply engage with the provided case information.","question":"Did the student justify the answer using relevant reading information?"}]','moderate',0,5,'it gave me a new perspecitive on things!','i thought it was great','gemini-2.5-pro','gemini-2.5-flash-lite','CEO: Hello STUDENT, I am Kent Beck, the CEO of Malawi\'s Pizza. Thank you for meeting with me today. Our time is limited so let\'s get straight to my quandary: **Should we stay in the catering business, or is pizza catering a distraction from our core restaurant operations?**\n\nSTUDENT: I think you should stay in the catering business, but make it align with your company already. For example, you could only do the informal events where the staff and business isn\'t doing extra work that they wouldn\'t do at the resturant. Malawis is informal so it shouldn\'t change that.\n\nCEO: That\'s an interesting thought, STUDENT. Focusing on the informal side of things could certainly simplify our operations.\n\nHowever, the case states that wedding dinners and receptions make up roughly half of our catering events, and those are our largest ones, averaging around 300 attendees.\n\nWhy do you think we should walk away from such a significant part of our existing catering business?\n\nSTUDENT: That is a great point. I think it\'s important for Malawis to keep weddings as part of their business, but should set clear guidelines that all the workers need to do is make the food and help clean up after since that\'s what their job intails already. However, you can have your more experienced employees do this so they can interact with the wedding people but they shouldn\'t be in charge of bringing nice china and doing extra things.\n\nCEO: I see. You\'re suggesting we standardize the service level across all events to simplify things.\n\nBut the case mentions that for these formal wedding events, we bring "nicer china" and have more interaction with attendees. Evans believes customers are paying a premium precisely because they feel they are receiving the "highest degree of attention and customization."\n\nIf we remove those formal service elements, how do you think that will affect our ability to command premium pricing for those large, profitable wedding events?\n\nSTUDENT: You are not a premium company so you shouldn\'t be commanding premium pricing. People reach out to Malwais because they love the pizza and the company image. They aren\'t expecting a fancy service. However, this will still make Malwais great money.\n\nCEO: I\'ll push back on that a bit, STUDENT. My background is in high-end food serviceFour Seasons, Ritz-Carlton. While the restaurant is \'fast casual,\' the catering arm has been positioned differently.\n\nThe case explicitly states that catering is the "most profitable part of the restaurant operation." This is largely because, as Evans notes, these events command premium pricing.\n\nIf we follow your advice and stop acting like a premium service for these formal events, what does that do to our most profitable business line?\n\nSTUDENT: time is up\n\nCEO: STUDENT, thank you for meeting with me. I am glad you were able to study this case and share your insights. I hope our conversation was challenging yet helpful. **Would you be willing to provide feedback by answering a few questions about our interaction?**\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Great! On a scale of 1 to 5, how helpful was our conversation in your thinking through this case situation? (1=not helpful, 5=extremely helpful)\n\nSTUDENT: 5\n\nCEO: Thank you. What did you **like most** about this simulated conversation?\n\nSTUDENT: it gave me a new perspecitive on things!\n\nCEO: That\'s helpful. What way do you think this simulated conversation **might be improved**?\n\nSTUDENT: i thought it was great\n\nCEO: It has been a delight talking with you today. **Would you be willing to let me pass this conversation transcript to the developers to help improve the simulated conversations for future students?** The conversation will be completely anonymized (your name will be removed). This would be **a big help** in developing this AI chat case teaching tool .\n\nSTUDENT: yes\n\nCEO: Thank you for your time, STUDENT. Goodbye and have a nice day. I am going to turn this over to the AI Supervisor to give you feedback.') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE created_at=VALUES(created_at),student_id=VALUES(student_id),score=VALUES(score),summary=VALUES(summary),criteria=VALUES(criteria),persona=VALUES(persona),hints=VALUES(hints),helpful=VALUES(helpful),liked=VALUES(liked),improve=VALUES(improve),chat_model=VALUES(chat_model),super_model=VALUES(super_model),transcript=VALUES(transcript);
INSERT INTO evaluations (id,created_at,student_id,score,summary,criteria,persona,hints,helpful,liked,improve,chat_model,super_model,transcript) VALUES ('94f67875-e3a6-4786-b93b-12016e80da23','2025-10-27 19:04:29','9ae7cbaa-f59b-45d4-a3dd-e0ef6dbcc289',9,'Jacob demonstrated a basic understanding of the case by identifying the marketing potential of catering. However, his responses lacked depth and specific detail when pressed on the financial justification for the catering business. He struggled to recall key financial performance indicators mentioned in the text and ended the conversation abruptly. While he received one free hint, further probing would have benefited from more direct references to the case\'s financial data.','[{"score":3,"feedback":"Jacob\'s answers were somewhat consistent with the reading material, but he struggled to recall specific financial details about the catering operation when prompted. He mentioned market demand and advertising, which are present in the text, but missed the profitability aspect on the first try.","question":"Did the student appear to have studied the reading material?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"Jacob\'s answers were good but could have been better. His initial response about market and advertising was reasonable. However, when pressed for specific financial justification, he hesitated and then provided a somewhat unfocused answer about barriers to entry and ROI on the oven, rather than the direct profitability figures of the catering business itself. He also ended the conversation prematurely with \'time is up\'.","question":"Did the student provide solid answers to chatbot questions?"},{"score":3,"feedback":"Jacob\'s justification was okay, but only superficially referenced the reading material. While he initially mentioned advertising, which is in the text, he failed to provide specific financial data from the case to support the profitability of catering when directly asked. His later mention of barriers to entry and RO